I had the same problem and here is a solution/workaround. For AWT to work, the cocoa main loop needs to be started. This can be done outside jnius. Something like this works for me:
```python
import objc
from Foundation import *
from AppKit import *
from PyObjCTools import AppHelper

def runAwtStuff():
    # main program goes here

class AppDelegate (NSObject):
    def runjava_(self,arg):
        runAwtStuff()

    def applicationDidFinishLaunching_(self, aNotification):
        self.performSelectorInBackground_withObject_("runjava:",0)

def main():
    app = NSApplication.sharedApplication()
    delegate = AppDelegate.alloc().init()
    NSApp().setDelegate_(delegate)
    AppHelper.runEventLoop()

if __name__ == '__main__' : main()
```

I don't have context for the original issue, but I think I may be encountering a similar problem, where exceptions in my management commands are not being captured by Raven. 

As an example, I created a dummy command that just raises an exception in its `handle` method. In Raven versions <5.24.0, running the command via `./manage.py mycommand` will present the exception message on the console, along with a message along the lines of `Sentry is attempting to send 2 pending error messages`, and the exception will make it to a dummy Sentry project I've set up. In Raven versions >=5.24.0, running the command simply dumps the exception message to the console, and the exception does not make it to the Sentry project.

I've tested this on Django 1.10.3 and 1.9.9 with the same results.

My Raven and logging configs are the following:
```
RAVEN_CONFIG = {
  "dsn": "<mydsn>",
}
LOGGING = {
  "version": 1,
  "disable_existing_loggers": False,
  "root": {
    "level": "INFO",
    "handlers": ["sentry"],
  },
  "handlers": {
    "sentry": {
      "level": "WARNING",
      "class": "raven.contrib.django.raven_compat.handlers.SentryHandler",
    }
  }
}
```

In addition, I have a custom client class (basically just a subclass of the `DjangoClient` that passes `install_sql_hook=False`). I have included it in my Django `settings.py` file as so:
```
SENTRY_CLIENT = "path.to.my.client"
```

I've tried to investigate this issue by seeing how the custom excepthook is set up in Raven [here](https://github.com/getsentry/raven-python/blob/master/raven/base.py). It appears that `sys.excepthook` is only set when the `Client` is instantiated, but it doesn't seem like the `Client` is getting instantiated when the management command is run.

Please let me know if any additional information would be helpful.

@travisdmathis You can stack them. In order to get the regular circle to work, I had to use some jQuery plugins that I wrote to set the foreground font color to match the nearest; valid background color.

Of course, you can just add `style="color:{{background of container div}}"` to the foreground icon. This way you do not need to use JavaScript. But you will have to update this color value if you decide to change the background color of the container later on.

Here's a link to the [***JSFiddle***][1].

## Image

![screenshot][2]

## HTML

```html
<span class="fa-stack fa-5x">
  <i class="fa fa-circle-o fa-stack-2x"></i>
  <i class="fa fa-sort fa-stack-1x"></i>
</span>

<span class="fa-stack fa-5x">
  <i class="fa fa-circle fa-stack-2x"></i>
  <i class="fa fa-sort fa-stack-1x masked"></i>
</span>
```

## JavaScript

```javascript
(function($) {
  $.fn.getParentBackgroundColor = function() {
    var color = 'rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)';
    var parent = $(this).parent();
    while (parent != null) {
      var color = parent.getIntBackgroundColor();
      if (color > 0) {
        color = parent.css('background-color');
        break;
      }
      parent = parent.parent();
    }
    return color;
  }
  $.fn.getIntBackgroundColor = function() {
    return parseInt(this.getHexBackgroundColor().substr(1), 16);
  }
  $.fn.getHexBackgroundColor = function() {
    var rgb = $(this).css('background-color');
    if (!rgb) return '#FFFFFF';
    var hex_rgb = rgb.match(/^rgb\((\d+),\s*(\d+),\s*(\d+)\)$/); 
    function hex(x) {return ("0" + parseInt(x).toString(16)).slice(-2);}
    if (hex_rgb) return "#" + hex(hex_rgb[1]) + hex(hex_rgb[2]) + hex(hex_rgb[3]);
    else return rgb;
  }
}(jQuery));

$(function() {
  $('.masked').each(function() {
    $(this).css('color', $(this).getParentBackgroundColor());
  });
})
```

