The core issue here is that `char *` values, when coming from Python, are only valid temporarily (essentially for the duration of the function call): a `char *` is a pointer to memory, which we ask Python to allocate as needed.  So that `char *` gets assigned a temporary pointer, the pointer only stays valid as long as the setter, and then the later getter is accessing invalid memory.

As a workaround, you can use a full `def_property` to define your own getter/setter:

```C++

struct MyType {
    const char *a = nullptr;
    ~MyType() { if (a) delete a; }
};
py::class_<MyType>(m, "MyType")
    .def(py::init<>())
    .def_property("a",
        [](const MyType &self) { return self.a; },
        [](MyType &self, const char *new_a) { self.a = strdup(new_a); }
    );
```

but without the destructor, that will leak.  *With* the destructor, you might end up freeing things you shouldn't, so it probably needs another flag to indicate whether the class actually owns the pointer.  And by that point, you're probably better off just switching to a `std::string`.

